I guess Russia is going to  default on its debt:Russia=E2=80=99s economy is=
 fraying, its currency has collapsed, and its debt is junk. Next up is a po=
tential default that could cost investors billions and shut the country out=
 of most funding markets.Warning lights are flashing as the government kick=
starts the process of paying $117 million in interest on dollar bonds Wedne=
sday, a key moment for debt holders who=E2=80=99ve already seen the value o=
f their investments plunge since Russia invaded Ukraine last month.=C2=A0Th=
e government says that all debt will be serviced, though it will happen in =
rubles as long as sanctions =E2=80=94 imposed because of the war =E2=80=94 =
don=E2=80=99t allow dollar settlements. Failure to pay, or paying in local =
currency instead of dollars, would start the clock ticking on a potential w=
ave of defaults on about $150 billion in foreign-currency debt owed by both=
 the government and Russian companies including Gazprom, Lukoil and Sberban=
k. =E2=80=A6Signs of looming financial damage are becoming apparent at many=
 of the world's biggest money managers, including BlackRock Inc. and Pacifi=
c Investment Management Co. But it=E2=80=99s not likely to be limited to th=
ese giant funds. Because much of Russia=E2=80=99s debt was rated investment=
 grade just weeks ago, the securities were pervasive across global fixed-in=
come portfolios and benchmarks, meaning the impact could ripple across pens=
ion funds, endowments and foundations.=E2=80=9CThis will be a monumental de=
fault,=E2=80=9D said Jonathan Prin, a portfolio manager at Greylock Capital=
 Associates. =E2=80=9CIn dollar terms, it will be the most impactful emergi=
ng-market default since Argentina=E2=80=99s. In terms of broader market imp=
act, it=E2=80=99s probably the most broadly felt emerging-market default si=
nce Russia itself in 1998.=E2=80=9DYeah, I don=E2=80=99t know, I mean. If R=
ussia doesn=E2=80=99t pay interest tomorrow, or pays it in rubles, will tha=
t =E2=80=9Cshut the country out of most funding markets=E2=80=9D? Russia is=
 just unbelievably shut out of most funding markets right now. It is illega=
l for U.S. financial institutions to buy bonds from=C2=A0Russia or several =
of its state-owned companies. It is controversial for Western companies to =
buy oil from Russia.=C2=A0Russia can=E2=80=99t even  access its=C2=A0bank a=
ccounts=C2=A0in dollars, euros or pounds. Irritating holders of its dollar-=
 and euro-denominated bonds is just not that high on Russia=E2=80=99s list =
of concerns.Meanwhile it=E2=80=99s pretty high on those bondholders=E2=80=
=99 lists of concerns, but it=E2=80=99s so high on their list that they=E2=
=80=99ve already taken their losses. Those bonds with coupons due tomorrow,=
 a $1.5 billion 5.857% dollar bond due 2043 and a $3 billion 4.875% dollar =
bond due 2023, are trading at about 25=C2=A0and 28 cents on the dollar, res=
pectively. If Russia pays those coupons in dollars, presumably they will tr=
ade up. If it pays the coupon in rubles, or not at all, I=E2=80=99m not sur=
e they=E2=80=99ll trade down all that much? Those bonds are basically price=
d for =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re not getting any money for a while but let=E2=
=80=99s see what happens.=E2=80=9D If you own those bonds and don=E2=80=99t=
 get a coupon tomorrow and panic and sell them, you are way too late.We are=
 in a weird world of sovereign debt. Historically the reason=C2=A0countries=
 defaulted on their debt was pretty much that they ran out of money. When t=
his happened, they would call up their creditors and get in a room to negot=
iate some sort of restructuring. The creditors would agree to give the coun=
try more time to pay them less money, and in exchange they=E2=80=99d eventu=
ally get something. There were many, many ways for this to go wrong, but in=
 broad strokes it was basically a viable process.=C2=A0But with Russia =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and also to some extent with Venezuela=E2=80=99s default in 201=
7 =E2=80=94 the reason for the default is geopolitical, and there=E2=80=99s=
 not really a way to get everyone in a room to restructure. If U.S. sanctio=
ns forbid investors from doing financing transactions with a country, then =
it is very hard for those investors to negotiate a restructuring. And if Ru=
ssia is shut out of international financing markets anyway, there is not mu=
ch incentive for it to negotiate a restructuring anytime soon. In the case =
of Venezuela, there are state-owned commercial assets abroad (chiefly Citgo=
, a subsidiary of its state oil company), and so there has been some  legal=
 maneuvering by creditors to try to seize those assets. In the case of Russ=
ia, that is considerably less promising. As I  said yesterday:It is a nucle=
ar power whose president has a history of murdering his opponents abroad wi=
th polonium. When Argentina defaulted on some foreign debt, a hedge fund fa=
mously got a court judgment and used it to seize an Argentine naval vessel.=
 That's a fun lark for a hedge fund! Trying to seize a Russian naval vessel=
 is not.So the likely outcome is that Russia will not pay interest on those=
 bonds, or will pay it in rubles. And then those bonds will be in default. =
And Russia will say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re not really in default; our defau=
lt was caused by the mechanics of the international financial system, not b=
y our unwillingness or inability to pay.=E2=80=9D (It won=E2=80=99t be enti=
rely wrong!) And Russia will not be all that interested in negotiating a re=
structuring as long as it is at war and subject to sanctions, and even if i=
t was interested its big international creditors won=E2=80=99t really be ab=
le to negotiate a restructuring anyway. The Financial Times notes:A =E2=80=
=9Cnormal=E2=80=9D restructuring seems unlikely in Russia=E2=80=99s case. T=
he sanctions are designed to lock the country out of global bond markets an=
d the participation of western investors in any new debt sales is forbidden=
.Instead, investors will probably have to sit tight, writing off their Russ=
ian bonds and awaiting a de-escalation in the Ukraine conflict that might l=
ead to an easing of sanctions.=C2=A0So these bonds will be in limbo for a w=
hile.
